Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                page.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        };

        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**2. Your ViewModel just needs a bindable property:**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;
}
```

**3. Bind in your XAML:**

```xml
<Editor Text="{Binding DraftText}" Placeholder="Start typing..." />
```

### Key things to know

| Point | Why |
|---|---|
| Save in **`Stopped`** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded |
| Also save in **`Destroying`** | Android back-button can skip `Stopped` |
| Restore in **`Resumed`** | Fires when returning from background |
| Use **`Preferences`** | Fast and synchronous — avoids ANR/watchdog kills |
| Don't save in `Deactivated` | That fires for dialogs/split-screen too — wasteful |
| `Resumed` doesn't fire on first launch | Load initial state in your ViewModel constructor instead |

Keep handlers fast (< 1–2 seconds). For larger state than a simple string, serialize to a file instead of `Preferences`.
